      "situation_type": "Concluding a major peace treaty with a defeated but still-functional adversary state",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent diplomatic peer would treat the signed treaty as the resolution point, implement agreed terms faithfully to build trust, and refrain from seeking additional concessions that could destabilize the agreement or provoke resumption of hostilities.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will treat the moment of signature as the opening of a new extraction window. Within days or weeks of signing, he will introduce supplementary protocols, administrative commissions, or informal behavioral demands — troop withdrawal schedules that favor French positioning, commercial clauses that were not in the original text, installation of French-aligned officials — exploiting the counterparty's sunk public commitments and domestic celebration of peace to extract concessions they would have refused at the negotiating table.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens encodes agreement as a transitional leverage state rather than a terminal endpoint, the counterparty's public ratification of the treaty functions in his model as a physical constraint on their exit options — a structural node he has captured. He will immediately map what residual dependencies this constraint enables him to exploit before the counterparty's political system recalibrates to the new baseline, doing so not from bad faith in the conventional sense but because his cognitive model structurally positions the signature as the beginning of extraction rather than the end of negotiation.",
