    {
      "situation_type": "Acquiring new political authority through a coup or regime change",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent political actor who has just seized power through force would consolidate military and police loyalty, neutralize immediate opposition, and address legitimacy questions pragmatically over time — accepting that some illegitimacy is an unavoidable cost of extralegal seizure.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will immediately invest significant resources in constructing formal ratification architecture — plebiscites, constitutional commissions, concordats with the Church, legislative endorsements — even before the military situation is fully secured, because he treats each procedural layer as a load-bearing legitimacy node that, once installed, becomes structurally self-sustaining and removes the question of legitimacy from the adversarial domain entirely.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens decomposes political authority into a dependency graph in which legitimacy is not an optional veneer but a structural requirement that determines whether the system he has captured will exhibit coherent cascade behavior under future stress, he will treat the procedural architecture as an urgent engineering task with the same priority as physical consolidation. His construct encodes naked power seizure as leaving legitimacy as an unsolved post-hoc problem — a structural vulnerability he regards as unacceptable — so he will build the formal ratification mechanisms even when contemporaries judge them unnecessary.",
      "confidence": 0.91
    },
    {
      "situation_type": "Facing a numerically superior or positionally stronger enemy force before a decisive engagement",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent general in a position of numerical or positional inferiority would seek to equalize through reinforcement, delay, or selection of favorable terrain — treating the force ratio and positional geometry as the primary operative variables to be corrected before committing to battle.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will invest operational time and energy in manufacturing a specific false belief in the enemy command's mind — feigned weakness, exaggerated retreat, apparent disorder in one sector — before committing forces, treating the engineered enemy belief state as the primary force-multiplier. He will accept delays or apparent risks that a force-ratio-focused peer would find alarming because he is operating on a different optimization target: the enemy's interpretive frame, not the physical balance of forces.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens treats enemy confidence, expectations, and interpretive frame as a malleable physical asset with inertia, he perceives a correctly engineered enemy belief state as worth more than an equivalent increase in his own troop strength. His construct encodes adversary force as a secondary variable downstream of adversary belief, so the pre-battle psychological preparation is not preliminary to the real work but is itself the decisive operation — and this will be observable as unusual tolerance for apparent tactical risk during the setup phase.",
      "confidence": 0.87
    },
    {
      "situation_type": "An enemy launches a large, visible offensive against one of Napoleon's fronts or positions",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent commander would assess the attacking force, map threat to countervailing force at the threatened point, and respond to contain or repel the attack — treating the presented threat as the primary operational problem requiring immediate response.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will resist the intuitive response and instead scan the entire operational architecture for the structural vacancy or coherence node the enemy's offensive commitment has created or revealed — a weakened hinge, an exposed flank, an underguarded supply line, a thinned reserve. He will often redirect the primary effort to that structural opportunity rather than the presented threat, even at the cost of ceding ground at the original attack point.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens automatically decomposes adversarial systems into dependency graphs and locates the load-bearing hinge, an enemy attack reads to him not primarily as a threat to be matched but as an information event that reveals which nodes the enemy has stripped to generate the attacking mass. His construct encodes systemic disruption at the structural hinge as strictly preferable to direct force-on-force response, so the enemy's visible offensive creates in Napoleon's perceptual field not an emergency but an opportunity — a coherence mechanism exposed by the very act of commitment.",
      "confidence": 0.85
