    {
      "situation_type": "Needing to bind a powerful, proud, or potentially disloyal subordinate or allied ruler to the imperial system",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent political leader would cultivate personal loyalty through patronage, flattery, ideological appeals, shared identity construction, or explicit threats — treating the binding problem as fundamentally a relationship management or coercion problem.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will restructure the target actor's resource flows, title dependencies, and advancement pathways so that the actor's rational self-interest continuously reproduces loyalty as a behavioral output — installing salary dependencies on the Paris treasury, routing promotion through imperial channels, making the actor's local legitimacy derivative of imperial recognition — before requiring any behavioral compliance, so that compliance becomes structurally overdetermined rather than contingent on sentiment.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens models institutions as engineered incentive machines rather than natural or moral orders, he treats the loyalty problem as a dependency architecture problem: the question is not 'how do I convince this person to be loyal?' but 'how do I restructure this person's node in the dependency graph so that their rational behavior automatically produces loyalty as output?' His construct encodes sentiment-based binding as structurally unreliable — a load-bearing node made of the wrong material — so he will engineer the dependency before requiring the compliance, which an observer will see as unusually systematic institutional redesign directed at specific individuals.",
