    {
      "situation_type": "Encountering a structural disadvantage that cannot be overcome on its own competitive terms (naval inferiority, legal illegitimacy, overwhelming numerical deficit)",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent strategist would attempt to compensate within the existing competitive dimension — building more ships, seeking legal endorsement, recruiting more troops — or would accept the disadvantage as a fixed constraint and plan around it.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will redefine the competitive axis itself, relocating the contest to a domain where his existing assets convert into the relevant currency: transforming naval inferiority into economic coercion (Continental System), converting legal illegitimacy into procedural legitimacy engineering (plebiscite), reframing a numerical deficit as a psychological manipulation opportunity (manufactured enemy overconfidence). He will treat the adversary's chosen dimension of competition as a variable rather than as a fixed given.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens encodes the competitive domain as itself a structural node subject to manipulation, he perceives an unwinnable dimension not as a constraint to optimize within but as evidence that the adversary has successfully imposed their dependency structure on the contest — a node he can attack by shifting the domain. His construct encodes persistence on a losing dimension as a category error equivalent to accepting the enemy's framing, so domain-shift is not a fallback option but a primary strategic reflex triggered by structural asymmetry.",
      "confidence": 0.84
    },
    {
      "situation_type": "Managing an expanding empire with multiple simultaneous theaters and increasing numbers of subordinate commanders and administrators",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent executive or commander faced with organizational scaling would design toward distributed authority — creating capable subordinate decision-makers with clear mandates, accepting some strategic incoherence as the necessary cost of geographic coverage, and building feedback systems to monitor quality.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will extend the centralized model and increase his own personal work rate rather than redesign toward distributed authority. He will treat ministerial and marshal-level intermediaries as fidelity-degradation mechanisms and maintain himself as the singular decision bottleneck, compensating through extreme throughput — dictating to multiple secretaries, sleeping minimally, issuing direct operational orders to corps commanders thousands of miles away — even when theater information latency has structurally broken the assumptions on which centralized real-time command depends.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens models intermediary decision nodes as coherence-degradation mechanisms rather than as scalability solutions, delegation reads to him not as management but as quality-control failure — a structural defect he is unwilling to introduce into a system whose coherence he treats as the source of its superiority. His construct encodes centralized high-throughput control as the coherence guarantee itself, so he will experience organizational scaling pressure as a demand to increase his own processing speed rather than as a signal to redesign the architecture, even when the information environment has made the model's enabling assumptions false.",
      "confidence": 0.86
    },
    {
      "situation_type": "Deploying a military or administrative method that has succeeded consistently across multiple prior campaigns or territories",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent commander would conduct at least an implicit audit of whether the conditions that made the method succeed in prior contexts are present in the new environment — checking for analogous local elites, similar logistical conditions, comparable troop quality, and compatible political structures — before committing to the method wholesale.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will apply the validated method — corps logistics, regime-installation formula, centralized command architecture, concordat template — to the new theater without systematically checking whether the invisible enabling conditions are still present. The more consistently the method has succeeded, the more confident he will be, and therefore the more blind to context-shift. He will treat the new situation as a deployment environment for the proven schema rather than as a case whose structural differences from prior contexts require audit.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens makes structural dependency visible but makes the context-dependence of the structural model itself invisible, his most validated methods function as the highest-risk transfer targets: each success updates his confidence in the method's universality without updating his sensitivity to the enabling conditions that were present in the confirming cases. His construct encodes analogical transfer from the most vivid prior success as the default, with no internal error-correction mechanism that fires before commitment is irreversible — so the behavioral signature is high confidence plus low contextual audit precisely in the situations where the transfer risk is highest.",
