    {
      "situation_type": "A major military or political defeat becomes publicly known",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent political leader would allow official communications to report the event accurately, or delegate communications management to press officers, treating the announcement as a reporting function that follows and describes what occurred.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will personally author the first official account of the defeat with the same urgency he would apply to seizing a decisive terrain feature — drafting the bulletin himself, controlling the sequence of disclosure, framing the magnitude of the loss, attributing causation, and ensuring his version reaches Paris and allied capitals before any uncontrolled account. The narrative operation will be treated as a concurrent strategic action, not a secondary communications task.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens models public perception as a second operational front whose terrain features decay in value as rapidly as physical terrain, the first official account of an event is not a description of a past fact but a strategic asset with a short window before another actor occupies it. His construct encodes narrative construction as requiring the same personal authority, urgency, and preemptive timing as physical maneuver — so delegating the first account to a subordinate reads to him as abandoning a decisive position, not as routine staff work.",
