    {
      "situation_type": "The primary strategic mechanism fails to produce its expected resolution — an enemy refuses to sue for peace after the capture of their capital or a decisive battlefield victory",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent strategist, upon observing that the primary mechanism has failed to produce the anticipated cascade, would treat this as a signal to revise the strategic frame — constructing alternative resolution paths, reconsidering whether the adversary's cost structure matches the model's assumptions, and explicitly planning for a different terminal state.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will interpret the failure to produce the expected cascade as a delay within the existing frame rather than as evidence that the frame is wrong. He will increase investment in the same mechanism — deeper penetration, longer occupation, more punishing terms — and resist converting the failure into a decision to switch schemas, because his planning architecture contains only one terminal state and no pre-constructed alternative. The longer the primary mechanism has worked reliably in prior campaigns, the longer this frame-lock will persist.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens decomposes situations into dependency graphs with single defined resolution states and drives all resources toward producing that state, a non-triggering cascade does not generate a 'schema failure' signal in his perceptual system — it generates a 'cascade delayed, increase input' signal. His construct encodes single-terminal-state planning as the architecture and contains no branching logic for scenarios in which the resolution state is not reached, so frame-lock is not a cognitive failure from within his model but is the model's structural prediction: it will absorb non-triggering as noise until the commitment is already irreversible.",
      "confidence": 0.88
    },
    {
      "situation_type": "Facing a choice between fulfilling a conventional duty obligation (remaining with an army, honoring an oath, accepting a role's constraints) and taking an action that preserves strategic optionality at severe reputational cost",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent commander or political leader operating within conventional role norms would fulfill the duty obligation, treating institutional loyalty and personal honor as constraints prior to strategic calculation — accepting the reputational cost of defection as a permanent liability.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will choose the path that preserves the irreplaceable future option even at severe reputational cost — abandoning armies, departing in secret, breaking public commitments — because his causal model treats reputation as downstream of power rather than as a precondition for it. He will execute this choice without the hesitation or guilt a duty-frame actor would exhibit, and will rationalize it in structural terms: the option that was abandoned was not irreplaceable, while the one preserved was.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens evaluates choices by comparative recovery profiles rather than by role obligations, his decision architecture encodes asymmetric reversibility as the primary variable and treats honor and duty as secondary considerations — legitimate inputs only when they happen to align with optionality preservation. His construct explicitly encodes the belief that reputation is downstream of power, so reputational damage from a strategically reversible defection reads to him not as a permanent liability but as a recoverable cost, provided the preserved option restores the power base that generates reputation.",
      "confidence": 0.83
