    {
      "situation_type": "Designing a legal code, institutional structure, or administrative system for a newly acquired territory",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent administrator would design the institution to address the immediate governance needs of the territory — resolving current legal ambiguities, establishing functional administration, satisfying the current population's most pressing demands — with future-state considerations as secondary.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will design the institution with explicit attention to the incentive constraints it will impose on successor regimes and future opponents who did not participate in its creation — building in social dependencies, property rights structures, and procedural requirements that make dismantlement more costly for any successor than maintenance. He will treat irreversibility itself as a design specification, investing in features whose primary value is realized after his own occupancy of power, because he models future adversarial actors' rational incentives as a manipulable variable in the present.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens models institutional architecture as a system of engineered incentive constraints on future rational actors, the design problem extends temporally beyond the current political moment to the distribution of future actors who will inherit the system. His construct encodes future-adversary incentive modeling as the primary design criterion and explicitly treats irreversibility as a design target, so the observable behavioral signature is investment in institution features whose value is not visible in the current political moment — features that a present-actor-optimization lens would identify as wasteful or irrelevant to current needs.",
