    {
      "situation_type": "Recognizing that current logistical constraints are imposing the same tempo limitation on all competitors in a theater",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent operational commander would plan within the shared logistical constraint as a background condition, seeking tactical advantages within its boundaries and accepting the constraint as symmetric and therefore strategically neutral.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will invest in organizational redesign — new supply corps structures, foraging systems, depot architectures, corps-level logistical autonomy — to escape the shared constraint, treating the investment as acquiring a persistent asymmetric tempo advantage over all competitors simultaneously once the escape is achieved. He will treat the constraint not as a neutral background but as a structural node whose manipulation produces a cascade advantage across the entire theater.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens treats logistics architecture as the actual governor of strategic tempo rather than as a support function, a shared logistical bottleneck reads to him as a structural node whose capture produces asymmetric advantage — not as a fixed background condition to plan within. His construct encodes the first actor to exit the shared constraint as acquiring a persistent tempo advantage, so the investment in organizational redesign is not administrative overhead but is itself a primary strategic operation, which will be observable as disproportionate command attention and resource investment in logistical architecture relative to what contemporary peers treat as relevant.",
      "confidence": 0.82
