    {
      "situation_type": "Planning a major campaign when margins are thin and the primary operational mechanism has already succeeded many times",
      "ordinary_response": "A competent strategist operating with thin margins would explicitly design for variance reduction — building contingency branches, maintaining operational reserves, identifying alternative resolution paths in case the primary mechanism fails — accepting lower peak-case performance in exchange for robustness across adversarial adaptation.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will design the campaign around the single-best-case outcome — the decisive battle, the cascade collapse, the capitulation sequence — and will drive all resources toward producing that state with maximum tempo commitment. Contingency branches will be absent or vestigial. When his situation frame is optimized for maximum-tempo commitment, the variance-reduction preference that exists in lower-stakes contexts will be psychologically overridden, because commitment-frame and contingency-frame are incompatible in his cognition.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens constructs campaign plans oriented around one defined resolution state and drives all resources toward producing it, the commitment-frame itself is the operative cognitive mode in high-stakes, high-tempo situations — and this frame structurally excludes the contingency-planning frame rather than running concurrently with it. His construct explicitly encodes that the commitment frame overrides variance-reduction preference when tempo is maximized, so the observable signature is a competent strategist who exhibits robust expected-value reasoning in low-stakes contexts but switches to single-terminal-state planning under high-commitment conditions — the very conditions where margin is thinnest.",
