      "ordinary_response": "A competent commander, upon receiving disconfirming feedback that a method is underperforming, would actively interrogate whether the current situation shares the load-bearing features of the cases in which the method succeeded — suspending template application and auditing structural differences before escalating commitment.",
      "framework_response": "Napoleon will absorb the disconfirming evidence as noise or as a temporary deviation within the existing schema rather than as a signal that the enabling conditions have changed. He will increase commitment to the method — more troops, longer occupation, more punishing enforcement — treating the failure signal as a call for higher-intensity application of the same approach. The behavioral signature will be confidence proportional to the vividness and recency of prior confirming cases, not to the quality of the current evidence.",
      "because": "Because Napoleon's lens makes structural dependency visible while making the context-dependence of the structural model itself invisible, disconfirming evidence from a new context does not trigger the 'schema auditing' cognitive operation — it triggers the 'increase input to produce the expected output' operation instead. His construct encodes analogical transfer from the most salient prior success as the default update rule, with confidence scaling in the direction of prior confirmation rather than current evidence quality — meaning that the more successful the method has been, the more disconfirming evidence is required to shift the frame, and the later the shift occurs relative to when it is needed.",
